Europe's heart, Germany represents a quarter of the EU's production, but it is in recession for the second consecutive year and is likely to be third. In 2024, GDP fell by 0.2 percent, after contraction in 2023 was 0.3%. The export, ace in the German industry's sleeve, is in severe crisis, as a result of the collapse of the manufacturing industry and the automotive industry, with Volkswagen who announced the cut of 35,000 jobs by 2030. The construction sector is also braking, blocked by inaccessible costs for those who want to build their own home. There is then the issue of immigration and security, perceived within the country increasingly out of control. Less than a week from the vote, the new polls > give the Christian-conservers of Merz around 30%, Weidel's AfD over 20%, the Spd at 16% and the Greens just below 13%. It closes the surprising 7% of the Linke - which in this way could beat its former leader Sahra Wagenknecht (founder of the BSW, at 4%) - and 5% relocated to enter the Bundestag of the Liberal Party of Lindner.
&nbsp;
<h2>MERZ, THE FUTURE OF THE MILLIONAL FUTURE
Friedrich Merz, 69, is considered the most probable successor to Olaf Scholz.> The leader of the Cdu - socially conservative and economically liberal - is seen as a representative of the traditional conservative wings of the establishment of the Cdu and preaches a complete reversal of the migration policy implemented by former Chancellor Angela Merkel between 2005 and 2021. Since he assumed the leadership of the party in January 2022, Merz wanted to end the years of centrism of the former chancellor > - his eternal rival within the Cdu - which in 2002 had removed him from the role of president of the parliamentary group. Speaking since 1994, in 2009 he decided to abandon politics. After the parentheses of almost a decade of great financial success as a consultant and businessman - in which he held among others the role of president of the Supervisory Board of BlackRock Germany, in December 2018 he announced the will to compete for party leadership.
Defeated twice, he was elected president of the Cdu in January 2022 and his election was interpreted by national and international public opinion as a profound right-wing turn of the party compared to the positions of previous leaders. Merz has already broken a tabooo in&nbsp;Germany&nbsp; since the post-war period, i.e. the implicit ban on traditional parties of any cooperation with the extreme right, having adopted at the end of January, with the votes of the AfD, a non-binding resolution on the right of asylum. Despite this move, Cdu's leader insists on excluding any kind of alliance with Alice Weidel's party.
One of the slogans of his election campaign is "Una&nbsp;Germany &nbsp; of which we can be proud again", in reference to the serious economic conditions facing the country. For Merz, the first cure to solve economic problems is to "hold bureaucracy under control". From the energy point of view, it argues that the decision of the previous government to close the remaining German nuclear power plants in the middle of an energy crisis was a mistake that contributed to the increase in costs. Another point in its programme is the reduction of the energy price of at least five cents per kilowattora, through the lowering of the electricity tax and network charges. On immigration, its plan provides for permanent border controls, asylum seekers' rejections and the introduction of administrative detention for foreign offenders pending expulsion. &nbsp;
&nbsp;
<h2>WEIDEL, THE LEADER OF ULTRADESTRA></h2>
Alice Weidel, 46 years old, is&nbsp; the candidate for the right-wing party Alternative fur Deutschland, of which she is co-president. Economist - he has worked for years for large banks such as Goldman Sachs and Bank of China - since 2017 he has been the leader of AfD at the Bundestag. His party, which before the Europeans was hunted by the group of 'Identity and Democracy' because his head coach Maximilian Krah said that "Ss were not necessarily criminals" >, was born more than ten years ago, becoming in time the party of 'fighting immigration'. After the victory in September of the elections in Thuringia and Saxony, Weidel is ready to assert himself also in the legislative elections. The theme of migrants is at the top of the agenda of the Weidel party, which promised that, if in power, within the first 100 days the German borders would be "sealed" and there would be "wide-scale repatriations".
At the last congress of the party it has also adopted the term "remigration" > to indicate the immediate expulsion of irregular migrants in the country, but also - according to some - of immigrants with German citizenship. Another Battle Horse of AfD is the attack on the outgoing government's energy policies. He has repeatedly stated that he wants to withdraw from the Paris Agreement and to "refuse any policy and any tax on the alleged protection of the climate". Weidel, despite being married to a woman, with whom two children grow, is then among the most daunting fairs of any policy of extension of the rights of Lgbt people. In line with this idea, at the last congress he promised that if he went to the government he will close all courses of "gender studies" in German universities. Finally, from the economic point of view, AfD's leader professed liberalism, focusing on a large cut of taxes and a 'super-sburocratization'.
