<h2>SCHOLZ, the USCENT CANCELLISHING TO REEST IN SELLA</h2>
Despite record improperity, > the 66-year leader of the Social-Democrats - the oldest party in the country that today faces a serious crisis of consensus - is firmly convinced that its co-operation and its composure will allow it to secure a new mandate under the leadership of the &nbsp; Germany, as it happened against every forecast at the previous elections. To the government since 2021 - after being Minister of Finance and Vice Chancellor of Merkel since 2018 - Olaf Scholz has managed to gather the necessary confidence to lead the "semaforo" coalition, shipwrecked in November following the release of the Fdp liberals from the executive.
In its 4 years at the Bundeskanzleramt has increased unemployment benefits through the Burgergeld - a social benefit aimed at skilled people at work, who are indigence - introduced the minimum pension 'Grundrente' and, on boost of the Greens, the Climate and Transformation Fund (Ktf) from 212 billion. Its recipe to try to regain land is a left-hand shift through a campaign in which the Social Democrats defend the rise of the minimum wage, the reduction of VAT on food at 5% and better protection for tenants. From the end of January, Olaf Scholz has strongly mobilized against his conservative rival Friedrich Merz, criticized for allying with the far-right party AfD in order to carry out the immigration law. He also accused his opponent and probable new chancellor, of being a "hot head". This is why he is nominated as a 'reassurance' of a &nbsp;Germany&nbsp; he is increasingly disoriented by the economic crisis > and geopolitical upheavals. &nbsp;
